Q1. In Python 3.X, what are the names and functions of string object types?
Ans. Python 3.X has three string types: str , bytes and bytearray. The str type often represents text file content, whereas the other two types typically represent binary file information.



Q2. How do the string forms in Python 3.X vary in terms of operations?
Ans, String types in Python 3.X do nearly all of the same actions: method calls, sequence operations, and even bigger features like pattern matching function the same way. Only str, on the other hand, allows string formatting operations, whereas bytear ray has an extra set of operations that make in-place modifications. Text encoding and decoding techniques are also available for the str and bytes types.

Q3. In 3.X, how do you put non-ASCII Unicode characters in a string?
Ans. that can be done using HEX and UNICODE

Q4. In Python 3.X, what are the key differences between text-mode and binary-mode files?
Ans, Text-mode files presume their file content is Unicode text and automatically decode when reading and encode when writing. Bytes are transported to and from binary-mode files in an unaltered state. In script, the contents of text-mode files are often represented as str objects, whereas the contents of binary files are typically represented as bytes.

